To contextualize the atmospheric evaporative demand across climate scenarios, the vapour pressure deficit (VPD) was calculated using the air temperature (T) and relative humidity values reported in Table 1, according to the following equations:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathrm{VPD}\;=\mathrm{e}_\mathrm{s}(T)\;(1-\mathrm{relative}\;\mathrm{humidity}/100)$$\end{document}2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathrm{e}_{\mathrm{s}}(\mathrm{T})\;=\;0.6108\mathrm{exp}[(17.27 \cdot \mathrm{T})/(\mathrm{T}+237.3)$$\end{document}
